76561197999956908,Recommended,292910,24138949,"Posted: 6 July, 2016",all,Agent Zirdik,"I'm a huge fan of Monkey Island, Myst, and Sam & Max, so I confess my guilt and confusion that Deponia flew entirely under my radar for a long time.However, upon a friend's recommendation, once I sat down to play it, I didn't stop until I'd finished the entire trilogy.The reasons why it absorbed me are easy to identify: Story, World, and Characters.The Story is fairly standard at a glance. It's about a self-centered antihero who thinks he deserves a better lot in life who by the end begrudgingly helps to save the world he so desperately wants to get away from. But escalating complexities in each character's conflicting motivations leaves you never quite sure who to root for, or who even to trust. Ultimately, it's a story about how people learn to tolerate each other.The World is perhaps even more compelling. On the surface, it appears to be a mix of steampunk, science fiction, post-apocalypse. The setting bounces between the garbage planet Deponia and the the floating utopia Elysium, and sets up a class struggle between them. But there's also a message about prejudice in the way it demonstrates the vibrancy and resilience of people who eke out a living among garbage, or the complacency that breeds in sterile environments.The Characters, however, made this game entirely. I said that it was a story about how people learn to tolerate each other, and to clarify, it's a story about people, none of which are innocent of selfishness or short-sightedness. But most of all, it's about how we as the player can learn to tolerate our antihero protagonist. And conversely, antagonists who seemed to be cut-and-dry evil begin to show more nuance. Even the female lead and romantic interest, who seems to be the moral touchstone and voice of reason behaves in strange ways that contradict her character.Ultimately its cartoon animation and colorful art belies its deeper adult themes, partly because the characters are wonderful and hilarious, and partly because you have to cope with all the things you've done to them."
