,Recommended,292910,13310433,"Posted: 10 December, 2014",all,Smasheroonie,"This is a review for the English version of the game.Deponia: The Complete Journey was fun for 99% of the time I played it. Few issues with voice lines when characters go from one sentence to another. Otherwise I've seen one minor glitch that caused the player character to move into the background but I fixed it by talking to a frog, naturally.The game has plenty of tough puzzles and good story points and progression, as any game of this genre should have. I like the art style, and the music, although a bit repetitive, is good too. The voice actors were fantastic and fit each character perfectly. Easy to use systems as well that prevent any sort of unneccessary tedium.I sunk 30 hours into this game as of my writing this while doing only one playthrough so far, which were all very entertaining. I recommend getting this if you are really craving a good point-and-click adventure.Edit 01/03/2016: Deponia Doomsday has just been released, the fourth installment in the series. This addition was totally unexpected, and as such my major gripe with the game, the ending, is no longer relevant. Therefore, Deponia: The Complete Journey receives a total recommendation from me."
,Recommended,292910,16304573,"Posted: 11 June, 2015",all,talgaby,"Short version: 85%If you haven’t bought the Deponia trilogy, the Complete Journey is the best option to experience this famous, not so child-friendly, but in the end quite enjoyable adventure game about a very egotistical protagonist and his struggles to save and/or leave his home planet.Long version:Deponia: The Complete Journey adds very little to those who already played the trilogy as separate games– it is nothing but a merged version of them. But it is excellent for those who are new to the world of Deponia or want to play the whole story without interruptions (if we don’t count the tutorials, since they were left in there for all three parts).On the surface, the story is about the struggles of the protagonist, Rufus, and his plans to escape the titular Deponia planet, so he can join the upper society of Elysium. But, looking closer, it is more of a tale of a very egotistical man who uses everyone to his advantage; not because he is evil, but because he honestly thinks he is doing the best for everybody by trying to do the best for himself. The result is not only some slapstick gold, but also excellent dialogues and character synergy between Rufus, his newfound love (Goal from Elysium), and all the others who help them or try to stand in their way.The characters and the dialogue are the strong points of Deponia, even though the plot suffers from a few problems. It tends to get sidetracked all the time, and as the games progress, the number of plot holes and abandoned story threads increase drastically.As a point ‘n’ click game, it shows an interesting difficulty curve: it starts off mild, then ramps it up to almost early 90s levels, only to end in some poorly designed or medium level puzzles. This creates a mixed bag for the Complete Edition, but a good bag nonetheless."
,Recommended,292910,22267282,"Posted: 6 April, 2016",all,Jero,"Deponia: The NOT-SO-COMPLETE-ANYMORE journey contains three of the now four Deponia games. You play as Rufus. A stupid, selfish, arrogant, sexist, possibly racist tinkerer prick who's tired of living on his garbage homeworld called Deponia and would rather spend his life on Elysium, a paradise where the elite resides high above the clouds. Will he reach this destination? There's like three games and all of them are named after the junk planet he's trying to escape from so your guess is as good as mine. Rufus at first I thought was going to be a generic point 'n click main character. The selfish, anti-social a-hole who is hated by everyone and will do anything to accomplish his goals, but still has a heart of gold yadda yadda, but this isn't the case. While he definitely has an arc throughout the entire collection, I feel that Rufus is a more of a unique character than most protagonists. He's essentially the mondern Guybrush Threepwood, but he's actually a bad person who will never think things through and hurts loads of people regardless of whether they deserve it or not. Sure, he sometimes does good things or at least tries, but the only reason he even would go through with it is for selfish reasons and I kind of like that. The game bursts with character. Rufus could nod and it will get a chuckle out of me. If you miss the old funny lucasarts point and clicks then you should definitely get this game.If you're familiar with the genre then you know that this can only mean one thing: MOON LOGIC. You know the drill! This means you have to seduce all three personalities of one lady who all want you to do a different thing and one of them wants a romantic dinner, but the only decent restaurant in town serves disgusting platypus so that needs to go off the menu which means you gotta hatch all these eggs so each kind of platypus will protect their babies and they won't be turned into platypus dinner, but to hatch the eggs you need finish all these minigames, but to even get all that information you need to be a member of the official platypus club and get the official platypus guide for dummies which means you need a membership card, but it can only be found in fortune cookies, but we have no money to order any food and OH MY GOD WE STILL HAVE TO DO THE OTHER TWO OW MY HEAD.It's pretty bad. The second game is the worst at this as the ridiculousness starts right away while the first and second installment increase the complexity gradually. Heck, it's only one where you can actually have a FULL inventory. That's just cruel, but honestly, if the game keeps throwing my humourous situations like these then I don't really mind and in all fairness, they leave in enough hints to give you an idea what you're supposed to be doing. It can be really fun to try and figure these things out. Even then you usually have a always helpful to-do-list that helps you keep track of your goals whenever you get sidetracked by another crazy situation. Even getting stuck or trying to combine random inventory items or something dumb like that will at least lead to a funny line every once and a while and when you do succeed you'll get rewarded with more plot.Though I have to admit, the first game is the weakest in this case. You've got the standard complex puzzles, but not a lot of pay off to make up for it. The second half doesn't have as many characters to talk to as the first which results in less laughs. The first game is just there to mostly sets up the universe and there's very little accomplished with each action especially compared to the later games. Oh and the ending is terrible and I can only describe as mood whiplash, because I don't want to spoil it. So I'm glad that there's a fourth game that adds another layer to it that makes it work.The music is good, though the looping is easy to get on your nerves especially in the first game because they remix the same song three times and god forbid you get stuck for more than fifteen minutes trying to figure out how to progress. It's maddening. The graphics are great. Backgrounds look beautiful, but unfortunately objects that you can interact with occasionally blend in with the rest. There is a feature that highlights items of importance, but the game never informs you of this.The character designs are great too. They're very expressive and unique. The animation isn't bad either, but noticeably limited. Sometimes characters won't move their lips when they talk or will look just weird like for example having this comfortable walking animation for a scene that's supposed to be running away from danger.So if you're fan of funny Point 'n click games, get this one unless you don't like offensive humour in which case might I recommend Tim Schafers Broken Age a game FOR BABIES. NO. REAL MEN PLAY THIS EIGHTEEN HOUR LONG GERMAN POINT 'N CLICK VIDEO GAMEING SERIES YOU SCHWEINHU-oh also the singing is weird. I don't get any of it."
