76561198030367984,Recommended,292910,17937039,"Posted: 7 September, 2015",all,ExaltedDuck,"I think I've plyaed the entire libraries of Sierra/Dynamx and LucasArts games from the early 80's until around 2000.  I love a good point'n'click adventure.  And this is a good point'n'click adventure.  The music and voice acting are top notch, the puzzles are almost on par with Schafer/Grossman/Gilbert.  Deponia seems to be imagined in a similar vein to the mid-90's LucasArts games, with an absurd setting and hero you're never really sure why you should like but regardless still do.  It kind of felt like the trilogy's narrative through the first two titles was quite a bit more focused than the third, with Goodbye Deponia losing enough cohesiveness that it made me like the first two less.  Especially, the ending didn't really seem to make sense with the characters' personalities.  But at its core, there is a clear love for kooky comedic puzzle solving, and I certainly hope the gang at Daedalic has a long and successful career to continue to express it."
