,Recommended,292910,15217447,"Posted: 5 April, 2015",all,alison,"[Deutsch unter]This adventure trilogy is a lot more fun than i expected it would be. It looks a bit slapstick and twee from the outside, but it's actually a fairly adult game filled with clever jokes and tricky puzzles. I played it in German and have absolutely no idea how they were able to translate some of the hilarious puns, but i almost want to play it again just to find out. Unfortunately the main character is a complete♥♥♥♥♥♥ and i think this is the game's biggest failing. In the first episode his antics are amusing and it's fun to play the rascal, but when the game tries to gets more dramatic toward the end, all the awful things you had to do to get there kind of make you wish he would just die already. Some of the jokes along the way are pretty tasteless, but the ones that hit are insanely funny. And i do admire the ambition of some of the less traditional puzzles and storyline elements. Overall this wasn't as fun for me as Edna and Harvey: The Breakout, but definitely worth a playthrough.Ich hab dieses Spiel gekauft nach ich mich nur ne halbe Stunde mit ""Edna bricht aus"" beschäftigte, so en tolles Spiel war das. Diese ist auf einige Arten noch besser, aber Problemen gibt's auch. Die schönste Sachen, nach meiner Meinung, sind die Wortspielen. Ich habe keine Ahnung beispielerweise wie die dem Ersatzkatzenwitz übersetzen könnten... Aber man, was war's superlustig, obwohl das Rätsel voll undurchsichtig ist (wie mit Edna...) Andereseits du spielst als nen kompletten♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ der absolut nicht zu mögen ist. Genau in die dramatischen Teilen ist das Scheiß, weil 's Mitgefühl mit dem Charakter einfach nicht da ist. Trotzdem, die meiste Witzen sind unglaublich lustig und der Entwicklerkommentar rockt, also kauf ma schon!"
76561198086357013,Recommended,292910,15451359,"Posted: 19 April, 2015",all,Dropeter,"Superman is the most boring hero ever. Even though he has some weaknesses, the person itself is just too perfect to be very likable (in my opinion, that is). The reason I'm stating this, is that Deponia has gathered some critique that its main protagonist is too much an a**hole for players to really get into the story, something that is very important for adventure games. I disagree with that. Good adventure games do not have a perfect protagonist, lest they would be too short. Deponia's story of two people trying to overcome the impossibility of leaving a life full of trash would never be as enjoyable as it is now if most of the obstacles that lie in the way weren't created by the protagonist itself! Of course the player does not like the way Rufus is handling things, but this creates hilarious possibilities for puzzles that otherwise never would have happened. Deponias story is very strong because the player knows why he is in a certain situation. There isn't some kind of Deus Ex Machina that throws us back every time we make some progress in our mission, no, we do it ourselves. This creates, besides a lot of comical events, also a story that you really want to complete, since you know what you are fighting against.Rufus may not be the most social being on the planet of Deponia, but at least his story is far from boring. Something a perfect protagonist never would have achieved."
76561198023787971,Recommended,292910,16370727,"Posted: 13 June, 2015",all,Aramillis,"I love this game. I never thought I'd get into point-and-click adventures, but this one's different. I'll admit I used a walkthrough, but I never thought a part was unfair, just obscure. The main part of this game is its story, and the story that this game tells is fantastic. Rufus is the worst sort of person, let's be clear about that, but every other character serves as a counterexample to Rufus. Plus, it makes it more fun to see him get beat up. Also, this game is extremely self-aware of all its tropes and themes, and it adds immensly to its charm. I'd say if you are looking for an amazing story, take a look at this, but keep in mind that it's a point-and-click. That didn't stop me from enjoying it, and this game does have plenty of minigames, but keep it in mind."
,Recommended,292910,16302932,"Posted: 11 June, 2015",all,*+*+TheLizardKing+*+*,"As a kid, I remember playing countless point and clicks, becoming enraptured by the open worlds of Myst and Riven, the clever script of the Monkey Island games, and the subtle charm of Grim Fandango. As I grew, I wrote the genre off as dead, thinking that no game could rival any of the previous with todays graphical capabilities and marking the audience as a small, esoteric, mostly gone group. I am pleased to find out how indeed wrong I was.Deponia, sequel Chaos on Deponia, and the culminating Goodbye Deponia all deliver on several fronts. The puzzles are complex and daunting, the atmosphere alluring, the characters intriguing and unique, and the art breathtaking. It has a very big ""Fallout 3"" feel to it (in terms of aesthetic) and brings with it a very immersive and captivating story to boot.Play as the loud-mouthed Rufus, a citizen on the junk-ridden planet of Deponia, and self-professed genius. Infamous around his home town as a harbinger of accidental explosions, he grows obsessed with the idea of leaving. His destination? The mystical cloud-city known as Elysium. When a wayward escape attempt brings him on board a sky-ship headed for Elysium, he finds an Elysian woman in trouble. Ever the hero, but quite the klutz, his rescue attempt brings them both crashing to the planet below. Now, he must get the Elysian woman, Goal, back to her home, and thwart the evil plots of the mysterious Orgenon.That's the idea, anyway.I really really enjoyed this game. I actually anticipated coming back to it after a long day at work, and spent hours avoiding tutorials to try and figure out the puzzles. Lots of inventory combinations, lots of seemingly convoluted puzzles (that seem obvious once you figure them out...), and a HUGE cast of characters from which to gather information, and items.If I had any complaints, they would be few. The soundtrack, although absolutely wonderful, gets tiring at times, especially when you're looking at one screen for an hour trying to work out which way to move the lever to open the door. There is also an illusion of choice and a ""moral"" system in the game via conversation, but in reality, there are no other paths to the end result, and additional dialogue choices are either there just for comedic purposes, or to further showcase what an ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ the main character actually is. My final complaint will be spoiler free, but I absolutely despise the ending, although I understand why it ended how it did.I'd shy away from grabbing just the individual copies of the game. It is absolutely a three-part game, with all three parts needed to complete the story. Hope you guys like it! :]"
76561198159199115,Recommended,292910,16122087,"Posted: 1 June, 2015",all,RoxasXIII,"If you're looking for something similar to the Monkey Island series, this could very well be exactly what you're looking for. The Deponia Trilogy manages to capture a very unique feel as far as the story and characters go. The scenarios and dialogue can be quite humorous and the animation and gameplay are very similar to The Curse of Monkey Island. Rufus (the main character) is certainly no Guybrush Threepwood though. He isn't nearly as likable and comes across as ridiculously arrogant. It can be amusing at times but mostly it's annoying. He does grow on you after a while though and you'll be rooting for him by the end. I should warn you though, this game is NOT for kids. Although humorous, there are some adult references and language throughout the story and the final installment contains two F-bombs as well as a ""motivational"" speech that draws all of its humor from swearing, so bear that in mind if you plan on letting a younger audience play it. Overall, I would give Deponia: The Complete Journey 8/10."
