76561197975368055,Recommended,292910,18703930,"Posted: 26 October, 2015",all,Libertycrumpet the Lesser,"Overall positive perception.  Think of it like Monkey Island with a more crass spin.The main character, Rufus, was rather annoying to me.  He constantly had an inflated opinion of himself and could not learn from his mistakes, and as an engineer who appreciates failure as a teaching option, this bugged me.  He sometimes found himself in bizarre situations, but unlike Guybrush Threepwood, who found himself in bizarre new situations caused by banjo duals or by wayward denizens of undead pirate lords, these situations were often of Rufus' own making, so he deserved it, and when he found a way out of them with a self-righteous attitude, it just wasn't very entertaining.  Think of someone you've met who, even in the face of overwhelming fact that he screwed up, will pass off the fault.Puzzle crafting turned into a ""keep guide open on the secondary monitor"" routine.  If you want to solve it without a guide, you may be required to keep track of every single item that you can examine in the environment and a keep a record of a lot of conversations, and even then there are puzzles for which there is no hint in any of the ""look at item in inventory"" dialogue.  But if you keep a guide open, it isn't bad.Everything else though is very good.  The art is very expressive, the narrative is very well crafted and quite entertaining at times.  A lot of work went into the dialogue, and the songs between sections are sometimes hilarious (keep subtitles on)!  And the music, oh yes the music + background noises flesh out every scene.Overall, my impression is that this is a well-done game with an annoying lead character who drags it down."
