,Recommended,292910,13892024,"Posted: 8 January, 2015",all,CaptainAsmo,"Just finished it... and honestly I'm very mixed.The entire game had me sitting on the edge of my seat. Throughtout games 1 and 2, and the majority of 3 I was absolutely absorbed, and honestly I could see that a lot of work was put into making the game[s] interesting and exciting (with a couple of rly cool eastereggs).If I had been asked at anypoint of my playthrough if I would recommend this game (excluding the last hour of so of gameplay) I would have responded ""Yes. Definetly, it is one of the best games I've played."" but after finishing it, I'm no longer as sure. Other than a very unsatisfying ending that does not fit into the overall genre of the game (which is mostly comedy/sci-fi), the game also leaves huge gaps in knowledge given to the player. One of the biggest sins that a writer can make, is introducing a new concept, a new idea, a new revelation, in the conclusion. And many such things are done within the last hour of game 3. Charectors randomly transforming into each other, things disapearing, things randomly apearing, an overwhelming amount of teleportation, and other things I can't agree with.Game 1 makes a promise that Rufus will fight his fate with all his might, that his ego, his personality refuses to lose, that he will not be kept down or chained to a planet of filth.Game 2 makes a promise that Rufus will not hurt those around him, at least not on purpose, (with the exclusion of tricking people into electrocution, that's totally fine for some reason) but It restates that he will not give up, not even when it's hopeless.Game 3 confuses the everloving crap out of any sort of logic you may try to use. It creates question after question after question, and then instead of giving us some anwsers in a clever and meaningful way (as I had started to expect), it throws an ending that feels pasted on [and not even much like an ending] at us. Even ignoring the heavily unsatisfying ending, Rufus breaks everything that he as a charector stands for, and becomes what would be a true hero, even though it completely contradicts everything that he as a person, and as a charector stood for. He finally decides to give up. No crazy sceme, no sleigh of hand, nothing of what he stood for or represented. Just a flat, boring, cliche hero ending.""Goodbye Deponia"" never really manages to feel like a goodbye. It just feels like I need to open up game 4, even though game 4 does not(and the dev. promised that it will never) exist.Tl;Dr:Game 1 - Outstanding 9/10 would play again in several yearsGame 2 - Great 8/10 would play again. Introduces lots of new things to keep a long game from getting staleGame 3 - 4/10; Plot-Twist reveal mid-game actually quite obvious; Ending leaves more questions than it anwsers (and not the good kind); Unsatisfying EndNevertheless, most certainly worth a try, if only for the jokes and cool animations.Edit: Post contemplation I realize that the game is perfect the way it is, and that the ending leaves millions of questions, because the anwsers to them don't really matter, and in your head you are allowed to craft your own ending with such amounts of freedom that you are given, however retaining it's motion and impact. This game was the first one I have ever played, that has given me a sleepless night not because of fear, but because of conteplation.10/10 to the series.----Actual Spoilers----The two main problems I had:1 - Seagulls wife, ""Mom"" is never actually spoken of except in the one moment when it is used to♥♥♥♥♥♥off Seagull towards the end. It seems to be a huge part of Rufus' motivations and a very large reason for him being the way he is, but she is never spoken of except as an appreantly plugged in reason for Rufus to push/test Seagull. Considering the importance of Rufus' father to his charector, it should be assumed that a mother would be even more impactful (or at least as much so).2 - Dead goal falls out of closet. Alive Goal on boat. Goally turns into Donna. This means that A-Donna is a clone, otherwise there would be no reason for Goally to be Donna. B- Writers ♥♥♥♥ed up, cus without cloning you can't have 2 Goals - one that fell out of the sky with Rufus and one that didn'tadditional sins:The three kids? apparently 2 got eaten, but that's perfectly alright with everyone.Cletus jumped? but then ended up behind Argus with a weapon.Goal is happy? It's quite ovious that she knows Rufus sac'd himself for the greater good, but she seems happy about it?The Elders are cool with taking a bunch of hobos on their luxury cruiser? that seems like a huge point of conflict that was just glazed over.Cletus became Rufus? for the last couple of dialogue options Cletus loses his accent and sounds exactly like Rufus, which can make one wonder..................... a briliant move theatrically, but with unclear intent. Especially since Cletus/Rufus seems to be very excited and happy about his new role and his lousy ideas.Cowboy Dodo and the vainishing prison doors? Considering Cleetus managed to get out of prison and onto the organon cruiser, one would think that Dodo would manage that as well simpy by following him, but everyone from the prison except Cleetus simply ceases to exist.""Goal."" ""Toni."" What did I miss here..... I don't remember them ever meeting before that moment.... At least not while Goal was conscious...Awake? Srsly, the main heroine spent about 2.5 of 3 games being either impaired or dead... Or in game 3, both."
